<div id="review_2214033636" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2214033636" />
    <a title="megs_bookrack" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48328025-megs-bookrack"><img alt="megs_bookrack" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1532027727p2/48328025.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2214033636?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="megs_bookrack" class="user" itemprop="url" name="megs_bookrack" href="/user/show/48328025-megs-bookrack">megs_bookrack</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/36112638-little-fires-everywhere">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2214033636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7695054239915189041">The relationship between a mother and her child <b>can be</b> a beautiful thing, but let&apos;s be honest, it&apos;s not always. <br/><br/>It can sometimes be a <b>messy, complex and immensely stressful</b> relationship for both parties.<br/><br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1545349904ra/26778834.gif' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>In <i>Little Fires Everywhere</i>, Celeste Ng, weaves an intricate tapestry of such relationships. The resultant story is one of <b>family, loyalty, community and independence</b>. <br/><br/>When I went into this book, I thought it was a story about the adoption of a Chinese baby by a white family in suburban Ohio, show</span>
  <span id="freeText7695054239915189041" style="display:none">The relationship between a mother and her child <b>can be</b> a beautiful thing, but let's be honest, it's not always. <br><br>It can sometimes be a <b>messy, complex and immensely stressful</b> relationship for both parties.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1545349904ra/26778834.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>In <i>Little Fires Everywhere</i>, Celeste Ng, weaves an intricate tapestry of such relationships. The resultant story is one of <b>family, loyalty, community and independence</b>. <br><br>When I went into this book, I thought it was a story about the adoption of a Chinese baby by a white family in suburban Ohio, showing the resulting community reactions and interactions based off that adoption. <br><br>While it is true that there is an adoption in the story, and the baby is in fact of Chinese descent, that is only a very small part of this deeply emotional tale.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1509213260ra/24301197.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Full disclosure, I never cried, but I was definitely moved. I was angry at times, sad and emotionally drained. <br><br>I had my curiosity peaked, my temper flare and most importantly, this story made me think about it even when I wasn't reading it. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1545350057ra/26778838.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I think that is a sign of a literary fiction novel doing its job; challenging the reader and causing them to think. <br><br>I had never read a Celeste Ng book before and was deeply impressed by her subtle way of drawing the reader into the emotions, drama and angst of her characters.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1504762686ra/23811972.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>I must admit that Literary Fiction is not a genre I tend to gravitate towards. Like ever, but I am really glad that I went outside my comfort zone and picked this one up. <br><br>I think it helped that a significant portion of the story followed the perspective of teenagers, Pearl and the Richardson kids. I am not sure what that says about me, that I prefer that perspective, but there you go. <br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1573140273ra/28416859.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Overall, the varying perspectives really helped to complete the full narrative and I couldn't help but be totally engrossed in the lives of the Shaker Heights crew.<br><br>I definitely plan to read more of Ng's books in the future. Additionally, I did listen to the audiobook for this and thought that the narration was excellent!</span>
  <a data-text-id="7695054239915189041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


