<span id="freeTextContainer15379803815050242239"><i> “Most of the time, everyone deserves more than one chance. We all do things we regret now and then. You just have to carry them with you.” </i> <br/><br/>What an absorbing and character driven story!<br/><br/>Mia and Pearl have just moved into a new home in Shaker Heights, after jumping from place to place for years Mia has promised her daughter that they are here to stay. <br/><br/>Their house is rented from the wealthy and influential Richardson family. Mrs Richardson prides herself on doing everything ‘properly’. She went to</span>
  <span id="freeText15379803815050242239" style="display:none"><i> “Most of the time, everyone deserves more than one chance. We all do things we regret now and then. You just have to carry them with you.” </i> <br /><br />What an absorbing and character driven story!<br /><br />Mia and Pearl have just moved into a new home in Shaker Heights, after jumping from place to place for years Mia has promised her daughter that they are here to stay. <br /><br />Their house is rented from the wealthy and influential Richardson family. Mrs Richardson prides herself on doing everything ‘properly’. She went to college, got married, got a job, had kids. She has done everything according to the rules. <br /><br />Shaker Heights is a town built on rules and organisation. Everyone meets a certain ‘standard’. But when one of the Richardson’s family friends plan on adopting a Chinese-American baby, it causes a custody battle that splits opinions across the town. <br /><br />Soon Mia and Mrs Richardson are at loggerheads and she does some digging into Mia’s past. What she finds out may uproot Mia and Pearl’s new life they’ve made here. <br /><br />Full of rich characters - this book isn’t afraid to ask the tough questions. The characters are flawed and you can’t help but watch as it reaches its dramatic climax. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15379803815050242239" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

