    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3339987590" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3339987590" />
    <a title="Arini ~ Miss Casually Reading" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39722464-arini-miss-casually-reading"><img alt="Arini ~ Miss Casually Reading" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618540462p2/39722464.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3339987590?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Arini ~ Miss Casually Reading" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Arini ~ Miss Casually Reading" href="/user/show/39722464-arini-miss-casually-reading">Arini ~ Miss Casually Reading</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/34331079-little-fires-everywhere">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3339987590" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8940568154176952246"><blockquote>Reese Witherspoon made me read this book, and I cannot wait to watch the adaptation on Hulu because I NEED ANSWERS! And honestly, I might be the only one thinking this, but the Richardsons deserves better.</blockquote><br/>What’s the deal with this book? On the one hand, <i>Little Fires Everywhere</i> is a thought provoking and deeply empathetic book that grapples with a number of important subjects, such as motherhood, race, class, and other issues relating to the glaring disparity between family of the suburbs and the</span>
  <span id="freeText8940568154176952246" style="display:none"><blockquote>Reese Witherspoon made me read this book, and I cannot wait to watch the adaptation on Hulu because I NEED ANSWERS! And honestly, I might be the only one thinking this, but the Richardsons deserves better.</blockquote><br />What’s the deal with this book? On the one hand, <i>Little Fires Everywhere</i> is a thought provoking and deeply empathetic book that grapples with a number of important subjects, such as motherhood, race, class, and other issues relating to the glaring disparity between family of the suburbs and the nonconformists. On the other hand, from literary standpoint, this book has a lot to make up for.<br /><br /><b>The book features a huge cast of characters who are superficially portrayed and heavily imbued with hackneyed tropes.</b><br /><br />I was unable to see the MCs, which to me includes the Richardsons as well as Mia and Pearl, develop naturally. Most of the characterization is manufactured through long and tedious flashbacks. We know the things the characters do or has done, but we are not privy to the workings of their inner thoughts. For example, I know that <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Mia, forced by circumstances, accepted an offer to surrogate a child, only to then, back out from the agreement after she’s already carrying and flee with said baby <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. But I was curious of the whys and whether or not she regretted it.<br /><br />As for the tropes, we have the picture perfect family with Mrs. Richardson as the neurotic, busy bee, clueless mother and her four kids who are basically the carbon copies of the <i>Breakfast Club</i> characters. We also have the mysterious outsiders who ruin things for the locals in the orderly small suburban town of Shaker Heights, aka Mia the artist and her daughter, Pearl. We even have the cliché mentor who eventually has to die bcs why not? Let’s make it more dramatic so people feel even more sympathetic towards Mia. Well, guess what? I wasn’t fooled bcs I was actually appalled by her!<br /><br /><b>It doesn’t help that the writing constantly shifts from one character’s point of view to the next.</b><br /><br />I struggled to keep up as it doesn’t happen chapter by chapter; rather, paragraph by paragraph. Sometimes the switch even occurs in one odd but supposedly illuminating sentence relied by the omniscient narrator. This is not an unusual problem I often find in a book. However, in the case of this, it was annoyingly distracting and disorienting because the author gives out details not only on characters who are truly matter, but even on those who aren’t.<br /><br /><b>My biggest concern is the fact that I had to swallow many implausible plot twists and the unsatisfying resolution (or lack thereof) to some of the subplots.</b><br /><br />I felt like all the conveniences that happened in order to move the story forward were done in favor of stringing readers along to root for certain characters; thus, condemning the others. I’m sad that the book has to end with one character coming on top as the ‘saint’ while the other falls as the villain. The lack of closure is probably what bothered me the most. Despite everything, I’ve come to care for the characters, and not knowing what happen to some of them, especially the Richardsons, didn’t sit well with me.<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <b>
    <i>“Sometimes you need to scorch everything to the ground, and start over. After the burning the soil is richer, and new things can grow. People are like that, too. They start over. They find a way.”</i>
  </b>
</blockquote><br />I think, on the surface, <i>Little Fires Everywhere</i> has served its purpose which (more or less) is showing commentary on whatever issues it is trying to shine light on. The book is a great conversation starter as it poses many stimulating questions with multifaceted answers. However, so many details of the storyline left me high and dry that all the deeper takeaways I was supposed to be absorbing just went over my head. I hope the TV show will fix all these problems.<br /><br /><b>
  <i>(Read as an Audiobook)</i>
</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="8940568154176952246" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


