<div id="review_2113897507" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2113897507" />
    <a title="Kendall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42327848-kendall"><img alt="Kendall" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1637099251p2/42327848.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2113897507?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kendall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kendall" href="/user/show/42327848-kendall">Kendall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/34331079-little-fires-everywhere">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42327848-kendall?shelf=edelweiss-approved">edelweiss-approved</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2113897507" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16976739511330257124">Celeste Ng delivers a beautifully and insightful story about two families that seem like they come from worlds apart but are hauntingly connected in ways that they can never have imagined.<br/><br/>&quot;Sometimes you need to scorch everything to the ground, and start over. After the burning the soil is richer, and new things can grow. People are like that, too. They start over. They find a way.&quot;<br/><br/>Shaker Heights is a town that is &quot;safe&quot; and plays by the rules. From, the color/look of perfect little houses to our</span>
  <span id="freeText16976739511330257124" style="display:none">Celeste Ng delivers a beautifully and insightful story about two families that seem like they come from worlds apart but are hauntingly connected in ways that they can never have imagined.<br /><br />"Sometimes you need to scorch everything to the ground, and start over. After the burning the soil is richer, and new things can grow. People are like that, too. They start over. They find a way."<br /><br />Shaker Heights is a town that is "safe" and plays by the rules. From, the color/look of perfect little houses to our successful/money making residents. Mr. and Mrs. Richardson are a couple who STRIVE to live by the rules along with their four children (Izzy, Lexie, Moody, and Trip). <br /><br />But, here comes Mia Warren along with her teenage daughter Pearl in this privileged neighborhood. Mrs. Richardson starts to see that Mia has a dark and mysterious past that is affecting her family. Mrs. Richardson starts to see her children being drawn to Mia and her daughter Pearl.... where things are not living by Shaker Heights's rules.<br /><br />Chaos erupts in this privileged and controlled neighborhood when friends of the Richardson's attempt to adopt a Chinese-American baby......things start to unravel like a spider web between Mia and Mrs. Richardson. <br /><br />Celeste ever so beautifully pours her words onto the pages that leaves you connecting and feeling with these characters like you will not imagine. The amount of depth and insight this author has in her characterization is amazing. Her writing is insightful, inspiring, and just down right beautiful. Have I said beautiful yet?! Celeste does an amazing job connecting and interweaving all of the characters as one. <br /><br />The only issues that I had with this novel are on the aspects/backgrounds of the adoption/foster care system. I am a social worker and I work with biological families and adoptive/perspective parents and the situations are definitely not how they are presented in this book. An adoption process can take YEARS!!! This made me a little frustrated and felt like the author had some biases towards siding with the biological mother more then the adoptive parents. And, not to mention the issue of culture here.... A privileged caucasian couple can't raise a baby because they're not Chinese?! I do have to say... that this almost ruined the novel for me. I think doing more research on such a sensitive topic like this is crucial. Also, I think a lot of it is ignorance on society's part because a lot of people really don't understand that stereotypes/biases can feed into their viewpoints. <br /><br />Overall, 3.5 stars another fun and exciting traveling sister read!! <br /><br />I will leave you with one of my favorite quotes from this novel "What made someone a mother? Was it biology alone, or was it love?"<br /><br />Thank you to Edelweiss for an advanced arc. Publication date is 9/12/17. <br /><br />For our full Traveling Sister review please visit Norma and Brenda's wonderful blog! :)<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://twogirlslostinacouleereading.wordpress.com">https://twogirlslostinacouleereading....</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="16976739511330257124" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


