    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2476637896" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2476637896" />
    <a title="Richard (on hiatus)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73431206-richard-on-hiatus"><img alt="Richard (on hiatus)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525868884p2/73431206.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2476637896?book_show_action=true">Aug 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard (on hiatus)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard (on hiatus)" href="/user/show/73431206-richard-on-hiatus">Richard (on hiatus)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/35061545-little-fires-everywhere">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73431206-richard-on-hiatus?shelf=current-lit-us">current-lit-us</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2476637896" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7029430550369793021">I’m always intrigued in books that have gone viral, those massively popular, buzzy books that everyone seems to have read. It’s interesting to question the almost universal praise.<br/>Little Fires Everywhere is one of those novels.<br/>The story concerns Mia a nomadic artist and her teenage daughter Pearl. They settle in Shaker Heights, an affluent town, in a duplex owned by the Richardsons.<br/>The Richardsons are a golden family - rich, middle class and seemingly liberal, who live a near effortless existenc</span>
  <span id="freeText7029430550369793021" style="display:none">I’m always intrigued in books that have gone viral, those massively popular, buzzy books that everyone seems to have read. It’s interesting to question the almost universal praise.<br />Little Fires Everywhere is one of those novels.<br />The story concerns Mia a nomadic artist and her teenage daughter Pearl. They settle in Shaker Heights, an affluent town, in a duplex owned by the Richardsons.<br />The Richardsons are a golden family - rich, middle class and seemingly liberal, who live a near effortless existence in their big house in the most moneyed neighbourhood - 'A perfect life in a perfect place'.<br />The narrative examines the jarring impact Mia and Pearl have on the orderly lives of the Richardsons and their three young adult offspring. <br />The writing is smart, funny and sometimes moving, and about a third of the way into the book, when the central moral dilemmas of the novel toss,turn and tangle the main characters, the book becomes a page turner.<br />Maybe Little Fires Everywhere is a little overhyped (best book of the year etc etc) but I found it to be a well written, involving and enjoyable read.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7029430550369793021" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


